      <zones>
        <zone h='100000' id='2' type-v2='layout-basic' w='100000' x='0' y='0'>
          <zone h='98324' id='15' param='vert' removable='false' type-v2='layout-flow' w='98968' x='516' y='838'>
            <zone h='98324' id='1' param='vert' removable='false' type-v2='layout-flow' w='98968' x='516' y='838'>
              <zone h='8272' id='4' paired-zone-id='5' removable='false' type-v2='flipboard-nav' w='98968' x='516' y='838' />
              <zone h='90052' id='5' paired-zone-id='4' removable='false' type-v2='flipboard' w='98968' x='516' y='9110'>
                <flipboard active-id='1' nav-type='number' show-nav-arrows='true'>
                  <story-points>
                    <story-point captured-sheet='The Revolution In Numbers' id='1' />
                    <story-point captured-sheet='The Revolution In Number Cont.' id='3' />
                    <story-point captured-sheet='Shot Selection Transformed' id='2' />
                    <story-point captured-sheet='Positions Redefined' id='5' />
                  </story-points>
                </flipboard>
              </zone>
            </zone>
          </zone>
          <zone-style>
            <format attr='border-color' value='#000000' />
            <format attr='border-style' value='none' />
            <format attr='border-width' value='0' />
            <format attr='margin' value='8' />
          </zone-style>
        </zone>
        <zone flipboard-zone-id='5' forceUpdate='true' h='13927' id='9' story-point-id='1' type-v2='text' w='21419' x='53097' y='29424'>
          <formatted-text>
            <run bold='true' fontcolor='#000000' fontsize='9'>Net Rating Distr.</run>
            <run fontalignment='0'>Æ&#10;</run>
            <run fontalignment='0' fontcolor='#000000' fontsize='8'>1. Elite franchises used spacing as a force multiplier, while poorly constructed rosters that launched threes without defensive infrastructure fell to the bottom. </run>
            <run fontalignment='0'>Æ&#10;</run>
            <run fontalignment='0' fontcolor='#000000' fontsize='8'>2. The three-point revolution rewards intelligent construction, </run>
            <run fontalignment='0'>Æ&#10;</run>
            <run fontalignment='0' fontcolor='#000000' fontsize='8'>not volume alone.</run>
            <run fontalignment='0'>Æ&#10;</run>
          </formatted-text>
        </zone>
        <zone flipboard-zone-id='5' forceUpdate='true' h='24378' hidden='true' id='16' story-point-id='2' type-v2='text' w='41808' x='2119' y='29876'>
          <formatted-text>
            <run bold='true' fontcolor='#000000' fontsize='10'>Story of Strategic Elimination:</run>
            <run fontalignment='0'>Æ&#10;</run>
            <run fontalignment='0' fontcolor='#000000' fontsize='9'>1. Guards moved first because the math was undeniable as a pull-up from 18 feet scores the same as a layup but a full point less than a 3 from 22-23 feet.  Wings followed.</run>
            <run fontalignment='0'>Æ&#10;</run>
            <run fontalignment='0' fontcolor='#000000' fontsize='9'>2. Bigs were last to adapt but showed the most dramatic transformation. Era 2 produced the skilled bigs like Dirk, Duncan, Garnett made the 15-foot jumper an art form. By Era 4 that same shot migrated to the arc. </run>
            <run fontalignment='0'>Æ&#10;</run>
            <run fontalignment='0' fontcolor='#000000' fontsize='9'>3. The restricted area held flat the entire time. Teams did not trade layups for threes. They traded mid-range jumpers for threes while keeping rim pressure exactly where it was. </run>
            <run fontalignment='0'>Æ&#10;</run>
            <run fontalignment='0' fontcolor='#000000' fontsize='9'>4. Concluding that restricted area was never abandoned. The middle was eliminated and three-point attempt rates in 2024 and 2025 are still the highest ever recorded.</run>
          </formatted-text>
        </zone>
        <zone flipboard-zone-id='5' forceUpdate='true' h='13194' hidden='true' id='17' story-point-id='3' type-v2='text' w='23613' x='19742' y='33822'>
          <formatted-text>
            <run bold='true' fontcolor='#000000' fontsize='9'>Era 1:</run>
            <run fontalignment='0'>Æ&#10;</run>
            <run fontalignment='0' fontcolor='#000000' fontsize='8'>1. 3 point line was brand new and teams had no unified strategy around it. </run>
            <run fontalignment='0'>Æ&#10;</run>
            <run fontalignment='0' fontcolor='#000000' fontsize='8'>2. The negative 3PA correlation (-0.170) tells you that slower, more deliberate teams were the ones taking threes, using the shot as a deliberate tactical weapon, not a byproduct of pace. </run>
            <run fontalignment='0'>Æ&#10;</run>
            <run fontalignment='0' fontcolor='#000000' fontsize='8'>3. Turnovers were completely independent of how fast teams played (+0.039). No cause, no effect — just experimentation.</run>
          </formatted-text>
        </zone>
        <zone flipboard-zone-id='5' forceUpdate='true' h='11414' hidden='true' id='18' story-point-id='3' type-v2='text' w='32000' x='65484' y='35916'>
          <formatted-text>
            <run bold='true' fontcolor='#000000' fontsize='9'>Era 2:</run>
            <run fontalignment='0'>Æ&#10;</run>
            <run fontalignment='0' fontcolor='#000000' fontsize='8'>1. The 3PA correlation hit -0.548, the largest reading by far, meaning slower, grind-it-out teams were significantly more likely to shoot threes. </run>
            <run fontalignment='0'>Æ&#10;</run>
            <run fontalignment='0' fontcolor='#000000' fontsize='8'>2. The hand-checking era suppressed pace league-wide, and the teams running deliberate half-court offenses were leaning into the three-point shot as an efficiency tool. </run>
            <run fontalignment='0'>Æ&#10;</run>
            <run fontalignment='0' fontcolor='#000000' fontsize='8'>3. Meanwhile faster teams turned it over less (-0.248), suggesting they were running controlled breaks, not reckless offense.</run>
          </formatted-text>
        </zone>
        <zone flipboard-zone-id='5' forceUpdate='true' h='12042' hidden='true' id='19' story-point-id='3' type-v2='text' w='32516' x='50065' y='53089'>
          <formatted-text>
            <run bold='true' fontcolor='#000000' fontsize='9'>Era 3:</run>
            <run fontalignment='0'>Æ&#10;</run>
            <run fontalignment='0' fontcolor='#000000' fontsize='8'>1. For the first time the 3PA correlation fliped positive (+0.173) where faster teams were now the ones shooting more threes. </run>
            <run fontalignment='0'>Æ&#10;</run>
            <run fontalignment='0' fontcolor='#000000' fontsize='8'>2. The Suns, the early analytics movement, and rule changes that opened the floor all contributed to aligning pace and three-point volume for the first time. </run>
            <run fontalignment='0'>Æ&#10;</run>
            <run fontalignment='0' fontcolor='#000000' fontsize='8'>3. Turnovers remain slightly negatively correlated with pace (-0.072), meaning faster teams were still disciplined with the ball.</run>
          </formatted-text>
        </zone>
        <zone flipboard-zone-id='5' forceUpdate='true' h='12461' hidden='true' id='20' story-point-id='3' type-v2='text' w='29226' x='24258' y='70681'>
          <formatted-text>
            <run bold='true' fontcolor='#000000' fontsize='9'>Era 4:</run>
            <run fontalignment='0'>Æ&#10;</run>
            <run fontalignment='0' fontcolor='#000000' fontsize='8'>1. The 3PA correlation reached +0.625, by far the strongest reading across all four eras </run>
            <run fontalignment='0'>Æ&#10;</run>
            <run fontalignment='0' fontcolor='#000000' fontsize='8'>confirming that the fastest teams in the league were now definitively the ones shooting the most 3s. </run>
            <run fontalignment='0'>Æ&#10;</run>
            <run fontalignment='0' fontcolor='#000000' fontsize='8'>2. The Warriors blueprint worked and everyone copied it but the bottom chart adds the critical nuance: faster pace in this ear associated with fewer turnovers (-0.265), not more. </run>
            <run fontalignment='0'>Æ&#10;</run>
            <run fontalignment='0' fontcolor='#000000' fontsize='8'>3. The modern NBA figured out how to run fast and protect the ball in unison. </run>
            <run fontalignment='0'>Æ&#10;</run>
            <run fontalignment='0' fontcolor='#000000' fontsize='8'>Speed and efficiency were no longer in conflict. That is what separates this eras champions from the teams that simply chased the trend.</run>
          </formatted-text>
        </zone>
        <zone flipboard-zone-id='5' forceUpdate='true' h='13485' id='21' story-point-id='1' type-v2='text' w='21257' x='77260' y='35062'>
          <formatted-text>
            <run bold='true' fontcolor='#000000' fontsize='9'>3-Point Scoring Share:</run>
            <run fontalignment='0'>Æ&#10;</run>
            <run fontalignment='0' fontcolor='#000000' fontsize='8'>1. Era 4 three-point share of total scoring ended up being roughly 8-10x what it was in Era 1. </run>
            <run fontalignment='0'>Æ&#10;</run>
            <run fontalignment='0' fontcolor='#000000' fontsize='8'>2. The jump from Era 3 to Era 4 is the sharpest, confirming 2013 as the true inflection point when analytics teams committed fully to shooting the 3.</run>
          </formatted-text>
        </zone>
        <zone flipboard-zone-id='5' forceUpdate='true' h='17173' hidden='true' id='22' story-point-id='5' type-v2='text' w='33311' x='31201' y='20314'>
          <formatted-text>
            <run bold='true' fontcolor='#000000' fontsize='9'>  Bigs Redefined</run>
            <run fontalignment='0'>Æ&#10;</run>
            <run fontalignment='0' fontcolor='#000000' fontsize='9'>1. In 1980-1989 a Center or Power Forward with a three-point attempt rate above 10% was a statistical anomaly. There were a handful of pioneers in a league built entirely around post-ups and hook shots. </run>
            <run fontalignment='0'>Æ&#10;</run>
            <run fontalignment='0' fontcolor='#000000' fontsize='9'>2. By 2015-2025, they are the majority of all qualified big-man records. At the 10% threshold this growth is visible even in 1990-1999, when some bigs began testing the shot before analytics teams formalized the strategy. </run>
            <run fontalignment='0'>Æ&#10;</run>
            <run fontalignment='0' fontcolor='#000000' fontsize='9'>3. Three-point leadership also shifted younger across every era.</run>
            <run fontalignment='0'>Æ&#10;</run>
            <run fontalignment='0' fontcolor='#000000' fontsize='9'>4. The shot is now a foundational skill developed before the NBA, not a late-career adaptation. The top of the growth trend chart is not an outlier. It is the new baseline. </run>
          </formatted-text>
        </zone>
      </zones>
      <simple-id uuid='{D3CEA805-CD80-4E88-BEC0-FC4E2F78064F}' />
    </dashboard>
